         David Viniar: why he’s leaving Goldman
    








    By
        
        MarketWatch

Published: Sept 18, 2012 7:32 p.m. ET

Share


















































 



 


        Commentary: Goldman Sachs CEO delivered the good news and bad
    






















By


                                        MarketWatch
                                











SAN FRANCISCO (MarketWatch) — You don’t often get conference calls when a chief financial officer announces he’s stepping down. You don’t unless your CFO is a three-decade veteran and works for Goldman Sachs Group Inc. David Viniar who held the post since May 1999, or all of Goldman’s 

                            
                            
                                  
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
                                  
                                    GS, -0.91%

                            
                                  
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
                                         life as a public company was, in many ways, the face and voice of the investment bank. He endured through multiple CEOs including Henry Paulson. Read full story on Viniar’s exit.




Reuters



David Viniar,

Viniar presented Goldman’s financial results to the investment community on conference calls each quarter. He distinguished himself by not distinguishing himself: he was conservative, relatively uncontroversial.  In 2010 he testified before a Senate subcommittee with perhaps the biggest binder of financial data in history. He was a frustrating witness. Goldman usually does transitions well. Most of the backstabbing and internal power plays are kept from the public. Viniar’s successor is Harvey M. Schwartz, another uncontroversial guy. Read WSJ DealJournal’s blog discussion of the Viniar-Schwartz conference call.







From an investors standpoint, it’s always nice to see continuity. But in this case, maybe a shake-up would have been better news. After all, Goldman’s recent profits have declined to $4.4 billion last year from $8.4 billion in 2010 and $13 billion in 2009. The stock price has fallen at a similar rate, from $200 in 2008, to $119 at the close Tuesday. It’s a disappointing state of affairs that we’ll never really know how much Viniar was responsible for. Asked what the biggest risk the firm faces Viniar said “liquidity, liquidity, liquidity’ — a Wall Street CFO’s stock answer if there was one. Good luck David Viniar. We hardly knew you, which is probably why you survived so long.  — David Weidner. 


