Viniar stays put

By Mark DeCambre 



View author archive
email the author
follow on twitter
Get author RSS feed



 


Name(required)



Email(required)



Comment(required)










 

									June 11, 2010 | 4:00am
												


Modal Trigger






It looks like Goldman's troubles are getting in the way of the planned retirement of CFO David Viniar - seen here before testifying to Congress in April.
AP



Goldman Sachs’ superstar CFO David Viniar has been quietly considering making an exit from the firm where he’s spent his entire career, sources tell The Post. 
  Viniar, a three-decade Goldman veteran, considered one of the brightest financial minds on Wall Street, told a handful of close associates as recently as last year about his desire to retire — but then quickly put those plans on the back burner when Wall Street’s most profitable firm ran into turbulence. 
  The rough-going includes a civil fraud suit filed by the Securities and Exchange Commission over marketing of mortgage-related securities, a federal criminal probe on the same matter, and a civil suit brought by a hedge fund that bought a Goldman CDO. 
  At the same time, Goldman’s once-vaunted reputation is being pilloried in public. 
  A Goldman spokesman said that Viniar “has no plans to retire anytime soon.” 
  Still, sources familiar with the matter say Viniar’s earlier plan would have had him stepping down to pursue other interests as early as this year. 
  But those plans changed as it could be seen by the outside world that one of the firm’s top officers was abandoning ship. 
  “David is very much a team player and he’ll do whatever the firm asks of him,” said one source. Added a second source: “He’s so loyal he’s only going to do anything when the timing is appropriate.” 
  Among partners and clients of the firm, the Bronx-born Viniar, who turns 55 years old next month, is considered a rock star, lauded as much for his ease at explaining complex transactions as for his unpretentious, disarming manner. 
  Viniar joined the firm back in 1980 as an investment banker after graduating from Harvard Business School and has been the lead finance officer at the firm since 1999 — just before the closely held private partnership launched a public offering of stock. 
  On the Union College basketball team, the lanky 6-foot-1-inch Viniar, dubbed “Bones,” was a benchwarmer, but within the halls of Goldman, Viniar is viewed as one of the most valuable players, credited with pushing the firm to take short bets against housing as the mortgage market was upending its rivals. 
  “Under [Viniar] the [CFO] job became a whole lot bigger, said one former Goldman source. “He is a critical thinker who helped determine things like how much capital the firm set aside for certain lines of business.” 
  In fact, one source said Viniar’s various duties may be taken over by multiple Goldman staffers, when he decides to step down. 
 Goldman slid $3.03, or 2.21 percent to $133.77, a 52-week low yesterday.
